"Hurley J.V., Galewsky J.","A last-saturation diagnosis of subtropical water vapor response to global warming",2010,"Geophysical Research Letters","37","6", L06702,"","",,,10.1029/2009GL042316,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-77949841497&partnerID=40&md5=46e5713f9eb2b6bb8ed1d6395f225eb4","Department of Earth and Planetary Sciences, University of New Mexico, Albuquerque, NM 87131, United States","Hurley, J.V., Department of Earth and Planetary Sciences, University of New Mexico, Albuquerque, NM 87131, United States; Galewsky, J., Department of Earth and Planetary Sciences, University of New Mexico, Albuquerque, NM 87131, United States","We used boreal winter output from an IPCC AR4 GCM simulation to drive an atmospheric tracer transport model with water vapor last saturation tracers over the northern hemisphere in order to identify processes that contribute to the projected increase in specific humidity of the subtropical relative humidity minimum. Most of the increase in specific humidity at the relative humidity minimum can be attributed to last saturation within what will be a warmer free troposphere. The water vapor content of the relative humidity minimum is projected to increase in the 21st century primarily as a function of increased last saturation temperatures in the tropical lower troposphere, effectively yielding more water vapor via poleward transport. The increase in specific humidity is to a degree kept in check by a poleward and upward shift of baroclinic instability and saturation patterns that effectively yield drier air to the RH minimum via isentropic transport. Copyright © 2010 by the American Geophysical Union.",,"Atmospheric tracer; Baroclinic instability; Boreal winters; Free troposphere; Isentropic transport; Lower troposphere; Northern Hemispheres; Relative humidities; Saturation temperature; Specific humidity; Subtropical water; Vapor response; Water vapor contents; Atmospheric movements; Atmospherics; Global warming; Tropics; Troposphere; Water content; Water vapor; Atmospheric humidity; atmospheric general circulation model; global warming; Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change; Northern Hemisphere; relative humidity; tracer; troposphere; twenty first century; water vapor",,,,,,"Blackmon, M.L., Wallace, J.M., Lau, N.C., Mullen, S.L., An observational study of the Northern Hemisphere wintertime circulation (1977) J. Atmos. Sci., 34, pp. 1040-1053. , doi:10.1175/1520-0469(1977)034<1040:AOSOTN>2.0.CO;2; Brogniez, H., Roca, R., Picon, L., A study of the free tropospheric humidity interannual variability using Meteosat data and an advection-condensation transport model (2009) J. Clim., 22, pp. 6773-6787. , doi:10.1175/2009JCLI2963.1; Collins, W.D., Bitz, C.M., Blackmon, M.L., Bonan, G.B., Bretherton, C.S., Carton, J.A., Chang, P., Smith, R.D., The Community Climate System Model version 3 (CCSM3) (2006) Journal of Climate, 19 (11), pp. 2122-2143. , DOI 10.1175/JCLI3761.1; Couhert, A., Schneider, T., Li, J., Waliser, D.E., Tompkins, A.M., The maintenance of the relative humidity of the subtropical free troposphere (2010) J. Clim., 23, pp. 390-403. , doi:10.1175/2009JCLI2952.1; Galewsky, J., Sobel, A., Held, I., Diagnosis of subtropical humidity dynamics using tracers of last saturation (2005) Journal of the Atmospheric Sciences, 62 (9), pp. 3353-3367. , DOI 10.1175/JAS3533.1; Held, I.M., Soden, B.J., Water vapor feedback and global warming (2000) Annu. Rev. Energy Environ., 25, pp. 441-475. , doi:10.1146/annurev; Held, I.M., Soden, B.J., Robust responses of the hydrological cycle to global warming (2006) J. Clim., 19, pp. 5686-5699. , doi:10.1175/JCLI3990.1; Hurley, J.V., Galewsky, J., A last-saturation analysis of ENSO humidity variability in the subtropical Pacific (2010) J. Clim., 23, pp. 918-931; (2000) Special Report on Emissions Scenarios: A Special Report of Working Group III of the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change, Edited by N. Nakicnovic and R. Swart, , Intergovernme